DIV1.P:
But I am afraid, if we come to ex∣amin the Matter a little more close∣ly, we shall find that this is generally

all Stratagem; and that my Worthy Brethren who make use of it, have an odd Way of imposing upon the World, and giving of it one Term for another: Their pretended Gravity should be call'd Natural Dulness, for 'tis so in Fact; and where there is Fire, it will shew itself: Their Pre∣tence to Religion, in Opposition to Human Reason, is not because they have more of the First than their Neighbours, but less of the Latter: Their Canting Custom of Asking a peculiar Blessing on every Thing they undertake, is because they know their Skill will stand very much in Need of it: Their Disaffection to Human Learning is, because they know Nothing more of it than the Name; and so of every Thing else;

In short, I am tir'd of them; but I'll beg Leave to say, they are very pret∣ty People to trust Mens Lives and Limbs with.
